  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Specific legal definitions vary between jurisdictions, but typically include:\n\n1. Key common elements:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Attempting to hide the origin of criminal proceeds\n\n2. Typical legal definitions include:\n- Engaging in financial transactions to disguise the origin of criminal proceeds\n- Knowingly transferring funds derived from criminal activity\n- Attempting to make illegal funds appear legally obtained\n\n3. Most jurisdictions recognize three primary stages of money laundering:\n- Placement (initially introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing the source through complex transactions)\n- Integration (reintroducing funds as seemingly legitimate)\n\n4. Common predicate crimes often include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Organized crime activities\n- Terrorist financing\n\n5. Legal penalties typically involve:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\nNote: Specific details can vary by country and jurisdiction.",
